mporarily.\n    *   **Mitigation:** For goals under 3 years, consider **Bank FDs** or **Ultra Short Duration Funds** which are less sensitive to rate changes.\n\n5.  **Behavioral Risk:** The temptation to stop SIPs during a market downturn or to chase high-risk crypto fads.\n    *   **Mitigation:** Automate your SIPs. Stay disciplined. For crypto, allocate a very small, defined portion of your \"Long-Term Wealth\" bucket (e.g., 5% of \u20b917,800 = ~\u20b9900/month) if you must, but treat it as speculative capital you are prepared to lose.\n\n---\n\n### 6) Product/Fund Examples & Rationale\n\n*   **For Emergency Corpus & iPhone (Safety):**\n    *   **Liquid Funds:** **Axis Liquid Fund, ICICI Prudential Liquid Fund.** (Higher returns than savings account, instant redemptions available).\n    *   **Arbitrage Funds:** **Edelweiss Arbitrage Fund, Nippon India Arbitrage Fund.** (Tax-efficient and very low volatility, ideal for 1-year horizon).\n\n*   **For Bike Goal (Balanced Growth):**\n    *   **Balanced Advantage Funds (BAF):** **ICICI Prudential BAF, HDFC Balanced Advantage Fund.** (Automatically manage risk through a dynamic equity-debt model).\n    *   **Multi-Asset Allocation Funds:** **Quant Multi Asset Fund, ICICI Prudential Multi-Asset Fund.** (Diversify across equity, debt, gold, reducing reliance on any single asset class).\n\n*   **For Long-Term Wealth (Growth):**\n    *   **Flexi-Cap Funds:** **Parag Parikh Flexi Cap Fund, SBI Flexi Cap Fund.** (Invest across market caps based on opportunities).\n    *   **ELSS:** **Quant ELSS Tax Saver Fund, Mirae Asset ELSS Tax Saver Fund.** (Equity exposure with Section 80C tax benefit).\n    *   **Gold:** **Sovereign Gold Bonds (SGBs)** - Preferred over physical gold or ETFs due to added interest and no storage cost.\n\n**Disclaimer:** *This plan is based on the information provided and is for educational purposes only. It is not investment advice. Past performance of mentioned funds is not indicative of future returns.